---
import ResourceLayout from '../../components/ResourceLayout.astro';
---

<ResourceLayout
  icon="🧠"
  eyebrow="Mental health and well-being"
  title="Mental Health"
  introduction="Mental health is an important part of your overall health. Learn where to find support, what services are available, and when to seek help."
>
  <section>
    <h2>What is mental health?</h2>
    <p>
      Mental health includes your emotional, psychological, and social
      well-being. Everyone experiences stress, sadness, or anxiety from time to
      time, but ongoing symptoms that interfere with daily life may benefit from
      professional support.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Where can I get help?</h2>
    <p>
      A family doctor or nurse practitioner is often the best place to start.
      They can assess your symptoms, discuss treatment options, and refer you to
      counsellors, psychologists, psychiatrists, or community mental health
      programs when appropriate.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Counselling and therapy</h2>
    <p>
      Counselling provides a safe place to talk with a trained professional
      about stress, anxiety, depression, grief, relationship challenges, or
      other concerns. Many communities also offer low-cost or free mental health
      services.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>How to support your mental well-being</h2>
    <p>
      Healthy habits such as regular physical activity, enough sleep, balanced
      nutrition, spending time with supportive people, and staying connected to
      your community can all contribute to better mental health.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Is my information private?</h2>
    <p>
      Yes. Healthcare providers keep your personal health information
      confidential except in specific situations required by law to protect your
      safety or the safety of others.
    </p>
  </section>

  <aside class="notice">
    <strong>You are not alone.</strong>
    <p>
      If you or someone you know is experiencing a mental health crisis or is at
      immediate risk of harm, call 911 or go to the nearest emergency
      department. If you are struggling but not in immediate danger, reach out
      to a healthcare provider or local crisis service as soon as possible.
    </p>
  </aside>
</ResourceLayout>